# Command husky

## What does this command do:

git hook git-hook git-hooks library

## Installed from

For Fedora install using: `npm install -g husky`
For Raspberry Pi install using:
```
curl -o- https://raw.githubusercontent.com/nvm-sh/nvm/v0.40.2/install.sh | bash
source ~/.bashrc
nvm install 22
nvm use 22
npm install -g husky
```
For Mac install using: `brew install husky`

## Command path

For Fedora run: `~/.local/bin/husky`
For Raspberry Pi run: `~/.nvm/versions/node/v22.22.2/bin/husky`
For Mac run: `husky`

## Command documentation

Docs can be found at https://github.com/typicode/husky

## Command options

# Initialize husky in a project (creates .husky/pre-commit + updates package.json prepare script)
npx husky init
pnpm exec husky init
bunx husky init

# Run husky manually (used in package.json prepare script)
husky

# Add a hook (create the hook file directly)
echo "npm test" > .husky/pre-commit
echo "npm run lint" > .husky/pre-push

# Disable hooks for a single command
HUSKY=0 git commit -m "message"
HUSKY=0 git push

# Disable hooks for a shell session
export HUSKY=0
# Re-enable
unset HUSKY

# Skip hooks via git flag (not husky-specific)
git commit -m "message" --no-verify
git commit -m "message" -n

# Global startup file (runs before any hook)
# Edit: ~/.config/husky/init.sh

# Hooks are plain shell scripts in .husky/
# Example .husky/pre-commit:
prettier $(git diff --cached --name-only --diff-filter=ACMR | sed 's| |\\ |g') --write --ignore-unknown
git update-index --again
